<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n22007n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n22" href="#n22007n">N22 (VI.B.17)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n22all.htm#n22007n"> 7(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> p mortem</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">He dismissed Gladstone&apos;s post-mortem tributes to the statesmanship of O&apos;Connell and Butt, in contrast with their degenerate descendants, with the remark: &ldquo;In the opinion of English statesmen, no man is good in Ireland until he is dead and buried, and unable to strike a blow for Ireland&rdquo;; adding, with a note of gaiety not without its sad prescience: &ldquo;Perhaps the day may come when even I may get a good word from English statesmen as a moderate man after I am dead and buried.&rdquo; <small> William O'Brien, <a name="PORL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#PORL"><cite title="source">The Parnell of Real Life</cite></a> (1926) 21</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Right margin. </mm> </dd></dl>
